<doc id="227323" wikidata="Q276082" url="?curid=227323" title="Wilson's theorem">
<text>In algebra and number theory, Wilson&#x27;s theorem states that a natural number &quot;n&quot; &gt; 1 is a prime number if and only if the product of all the positive integers less than &quot;n&quot; is one less than a multiple of &quot;n&quot;. That is (using the notations of modular arithmetic), the factorial formula_1 satisfies

:formula_2

exactly when &quot;n&quot; is a prime number. In other words, any integer &quot;n&quot; &gt; 1 is a prime number if, and only if, (&quot;n&quot; − 1)! + 1 is divisible by &quot;n&quot;.

==History==
The theorem was first stated by Ibn al-Haytham . Edward Waring announced the theorem in 1770 without proving it, crediting his student John Wilson for the discovery. Lagrange gave the first proof in 1771. There is evidence that Leibniz was also aware of the result a century earlier, but never published it.

==Example==
For each of the values of &quot;n&quot; from 2 to 30, the following table shows the number (&quot;n&quot; − 1)! and the remainder when (&quot;n&quot; − 1)! is divided by &quot;n&quot;. (In the notation of modular arithmetic, the remainder when &quot;m&quot; is divided by &quot;n&quot; is written &quot;m&quot; mod &quot;n&quot;.)
The background color is blue for prime values of &quot;n&quot;, gold for composite values.
==Proofs==
As a biconditional (if and only if) statement, the proof has two halves: to show that equality &quot;does not&quot; hold when formula_3 is composite, and to show that it &quot;does&quot; hold when formula_3 is prime.

===Composite modulus===
Suppose that formula_3 is composite. Therefore, it is divisible by some prime number formula_6 where formula_7. Because formula_6 divides formula_3, there is an integer formula_10 such that formula_11. Suppose for the sake of contradiction that formula_12 were congruent to formula_13 modulo formula_14. Then formula_15 would also be congruent to formula_13 modulo formula_17: indeed, if formula_18 then formula_19 for some integer formula_20, and consequently formula_15 is one less than a multiple of formula_6. On the other hand, since formula_23, one of the factors in the expanded product formula_24 is formula_6. Therefore formula_26. This is a contradiction; therefore it is not possible that formula_27 when formula_3 is composite.

In fact, more is true. With the sole exception of the case formula_29, where formula_30, if formula_3 is composite then formula_32 is congruent to 0 modulo formula_3. The proof can be divided into two cases: First, if formula_3 can be factored as the product of two unequal numbers, formula_35, where formula_36, then both formula_37 and formula_38 will appear as factors in the product formula_39 and so formula_32 is divisible by formula_41. If formula_3 has no such factorization, then it must be the square of some prime formula_6 larger than 2. But then formula_44, so both formula_6 and formula_46 will be factors of formula_15, and so formula_3 divides formula_15 in this case, as well.

===Prime modulus===

The first two proofs below use the fact that the residue classes modulo a prime number form a finite field (specifically, a prime field).

====Elementary proof====

The result is trivial when formula_50, so assume formula_51 is an odd prime, formula_52. Since the residue classes modulo formula_51 form a field, every non-zero residue formula_37 has a unique multiplicative inverse formula_55. Euclid&#x27;s lemma implies that the only values of formula_37 for which formula_57 are formula_58. Therefore, with the exception of formula_59, the factors in the expanded form of formula_60 can be arranged in disjoint pairs such that product of each pair is congruent to 1 modulo formula_51. This proves Wilson&#x27;s theorem.

For example, for formula_62, one has
