====Proof using Fermat&#x27;s little theorem====

Again, the result is trivial for &quot;p&quot; = 2, so suppose &quot;p&quot; is an odd prime, . Consider the polynomial

:formula_64

&quot;g&quot; has degree , leading term , and constant term . Its roots are 1, 2, ..., .

Now consider

:formula_65

&quot;h&quot; also has degree and leading term . Modulo &quot;p&quot;, Fermat&#x27;s little theorem says it also has the same roots, 1, 2, ..., .

Finally, consider
:formula_66

&quot;f&quot; has degree at most &quot;p&quot; − 2 (since the leading terms cancel), and modulo &quot;p&quot; also has the roots 1, 2, ..., . But Lagrange&#x27;s theorem says it cannot have more than &quot;p&quot; − 2 roots. Therefore, &quot;f&quot; must be identically zero (mod &quot;p&quot;), so its constant term is . This is Wilson&#x27;s theorem.

====Proof using the Sylow theorems====

It is possible to deduce Wilson&#x27;s theorem from a particular application of the Sylow theorems. Let &quot;p&quot; be a prime. It is immediate to deduce that the symmetric group formula_67 has exactly formula_68 elements of order &quot;p&quot;, namely the &quot;p&quot;-cycles formula_69. On the other hand, each Sylow &quot;p&quot;-subgroup in formula_67 is a copy of formula_69. Hence it follows that the number of Sylow &quot;p&quot;-subgroups is formula_72. The third Sylow theorem implies
:formula_73
Multiplying both sides by gives
:formula_74
that is, the result.

==Applications==

===Primality tests===
In practice, Wilson&#x27;s theorem is useless as a primality test because computing (&quot;n&quot; − 1)! modulo &quot;n&quot; for large &quot;n&quot; is computationally complex, and much faster primality tests are known (indeed, even trial division is considerably more efficient).

Used in the other direction, to determine the primality of the successors of large factorials, it is indeed a very fast and effective method. This is of limited utility, however.

===Quadratic residues===
Using Wilson&#x27;s Theorem, for any odd prime , we can rearrange the left hand side of
formula_75
to obtain the equality
formula_76
This becomes
formula_77
or
formula_78
We can use this fact to prove part of a famous result: for any prime &quot;p&quot; such that &quot;p&quot; ≡ 1 (mod 4), the number (−1) is a square (quadratic residue) mod &quot;p&quot;. For this, suppose &quot;p&quot; = 4&quot;k&quot; + 1 for some integer &quot;k&quot;. Then we can take &quot;m&quot; = 2&quot;k&quot; above, and we conclude that (&quot;m&quot;!)2 is congruent to (−1) (mod &quot;p&quot;).

===Formulas for primes===
Wilson&#x27;s theorem has been used to construct formulas for primes, but they are too slow to have practical value.

===p-adic gamma function===
Wilson&#x27;s theorem allows one to define the p-adic gamma function.

==Gauss&#x27;s generalization==
Gauss proved that
formula_79
where &quot;p&quot; represents an odd prime and formula_80 a positive integer. That is, the product of the positive integers less than and relatively prime to is one less than a multiple of when is equal to 4, or a power of an odd prime, or twice a power of an odd prime; otherwise, the product is one more than a multiple of . The values of &quot;m&quot; for which the product is −1 are precisely the ones where there is a primitive root modulo &quot;m&quot;.

